<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="270" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="1.[136,778,1306,2093]" pageId="1" pageNumber="270">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,324,1451,1477]" pageId="1" pageNumber="270">Etymology.</emphasis>
Named in honor of my friend and colleague Edmund Jarzembowski. The specific epithet is to be treated as a noun in a genitive case.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="270" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[136,778,1306,2093]" pageId="1" pageNumber="270">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,312,1559,1585]" pageId="1" pageNumber="270">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Abdominal petiole short; body 
<quantity box="[676,778,1560,1586]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3699999999999999" pageId="1" pageNumber="270" unit="mm" value="13.7">13.7 mm</quantity>
long, forewing 
<quantity box="[308,394,1596,1622]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.1" pageId="1" pageNumber="270" unit="mm" value="7.1">7.1 mm</quantity>
long, with crossveins 2r-m and of 2Rs+M absent; 1Rs nearly perpendicular to Sc+R and to Rs+M.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
